#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/references/metrics.md savings=3%
M|Acti|tx|Metrics are the language of validated learning. The wrong metrics cr the illusion of progress while the startup drifts toward fl. The right metrics force honest conversations and drive real decisions. This guide covers how to select, im, and use metrics that actually matter.
M|Vani|tx|Vanity metrics make you feel good but do not inform decisions. They go up and to the right even when the pd is failing.
M|Vani|**Co|**
M|Vani|it|Total registered us (includes dead accounts)
M|Vani|it|Total page views (says nothing abt engagement qual)
M|Vani|it|Total downloads (says nothing abt retention)
M|Vani|it|Total rv w/o context (growing bc of more us, not better pd)
M|Vani|it|sl media followers (does not correlate w/ business outcomes)
M|Vani|it|Press mentions (feels good, rarely converts)
M|Vani|**Wh|** Vanity metrics can be manipulated, misinterpreted, and used to justify continuing a failing st. A startup w/ 100,000 registered us and 500 active us is failing, but the first number gets reported to investors.
M|Acti|tx|Actionable metrics directly inform decisions. If the metric changes, you change your behavior.
M|Acti|**Pr|**
M|Acti|it|Tied to a specific, repeatable action
M|Acti|it|Measured per cohort, not in aggregate
M|Acti|it|Have a clear cause-and-effect relationship w/ pd changes
M|Acti|it|Can be independently verified
M|Acti|**Ex|**
M|Acti|tx|\| Vanity Version \| Actionable Version \| Why It Is Better \|
M|Acti|tx|\|---------------\|-------------------\|-----------------\|
M|Acti|tx|\| Total us \| Weekly new signups by acquisition channel \| Shows which channels work and whether growth is accelerating \|
M|Acti|tx|\| Total rv \| rv per us by cohort \| Shows whether pd improvements increase monetization \|
M|Acti|tx|\| Page views \| Pages per sn by us segment \| Shows engagement depth and cn effectiveness \|
M|Acti|tx|\| App downloads \| Day-7 retention rate by cohort \| Shows whether us find lasting value \|
M|Acti|tx|\| em subscribers \| em open rate by cg tp \| Shows cn relevance and audience engagement \|
M|The |Ever|
M|Acti|tx|A metric is actionable if it demonstrates clear cause and effect. When you make a pd change and the metric moves, you can attribute the change to your action.
M|Acti|tst|** "If this metric drops by 20%, do I know what to do?" If the answer is no, the metric is not actionable.
M|Acti|**Ex|** Onboarding completion rate is actionable. If it drops, you investigate and fix the onboarding flow. Total signups is less actionable bc it depends on mk spend, seasonality, and press coverage.
M|Acce|tx|A metric is accessible if the entire team can understand it and access it easily.
M|Acce|tst|** "Can every team member explain what this metric means and find the current value in under 60 seconds?"
M|Acce|**Im|**
M|Acce|it|Use simple, human-readable dashboards
M|Acce|it|Display metrics on a shared screen or Slack channel
M|Acce|it|Define every metric in a shared glossary
M|Acce|it|Avoid jargon and complex calculations in primary dashboards
M|Acce|it|rp metrics in absolute numbers alongside percentages (percentages w/o context mislead)
M|Audi|tx|A metric is auditable if the data can be verified and traced to individual cs behavior.
M|Audi|tst|** "Can I look at the underlying data and verify this number is correct? Can I talk to real cs whose behavior contributed to this metric?"
M|Audi|**Im|**
M|Audi|it|Ensure data pipelines are transparent and well-documented
M|Audi|it|Maintain the ability to drill down from aggregate metrics to individual events
M|Audi|it|Cross-check automated reports against manual spot checks periodically
M|Audi|it|Keep raw event data accessible (do not only store aggregates)
M|Step|tx|A cohort groups us by a shared exp within a defined time window.
M|Step|**Co|**
M|Step|- **|** us who signed up in the same week/month
M|Step|- **|** us who done a specific action (e.g., made first purchase)
M|Step|- **|** us acquired through the same mk channel
M|Step|tx|Select the metric that best reflects the hypothesis you are testing.
M|Step|tx|\| Goal \| Metric \| Measurement \|
M|Step|tx|\|------\|--------\|-------------\|
M|Step|tx|\| pd stickiness \| Retention rate \| % of us active in period N who return in period N+1 \|
M|Step|tx|\| Monetization \| rv per us \| Total cohort rv divided by cohort size \|
M|Step|tx|\| Engagement \| Core actions per us \| Average number of key actions per active us per period \|
M|Step|tx|\| Growth \| Referral rate \| Number of invites sent that convert, per cohort member \|
M|Step|**Re|**
M|Step|tx|\| Signup Week \| Size \| Week 1 \| Week 2 \| Week 3 \| Week 4 \| Week 8 \| Week 12 \|
M|Step|tx|\|------------\|------\|--------\|--------\|--------\|--------\|--------\|---------\|
M|Step|tx|\| Jan 1-7 \| 200 \| 42% \| 28% \| 22% \| 18% \| 12% \| 9% \|
M|Step|tx|\| Jan 8-14 \| 180 \| 45% \| 31% \| 25% \| 20% \| 14% \| 11% \|
M|Step|tx|\| Jan 15-21 \| 220 \| 48% \| 35% \| 28% \| 23% \| 16% \| - \|
M|Step|tx|\| Jan 22-28 \| 250 \| 50% \| 37% \| 30% \| 25% \| - \| - \|
M|Step|tx|\| Feb 1-7 \| 230 \| 53% \| 39% \| 32% \| - \| - \| - \|
M|Step|**Re|** How does a single cohort degrade over time? This is the retention curve. Steeper = worse retention.
M|Step|**Re|** How do newer cohorts compare to older ones at the same age? Improving = pd is getting better. Declining = pd is getting worse.
M|Step|**Th|** If newer cohorts retain better at the same age, your pd improvements are working. If they retain worse, something is going wrong despite growth.
M|Step|tx|\| Pattern \| What It Means \| Action \|
M|Step|tx|\|---------\|--------------\|--------\|
M|Step|tx|\| Newer cohorts retain better \| pd improvements are working \| Continue current st; double down on winning changes \|
M|Step|tx|\| Newer cohorts retain worse \| pd or acquisition qual is declining \| Investigate recent changes; audit acquisition channels \|
M|Step|tx|\| Retention flattens at a certain week \| pd has a natural engagement ceiling \| Focus on deepening value for retained us \|
M|Step|tx|\| Retention drops sharply in Week 1 \| Onboarding or first-use exp is broken \| Redesign activation flow \|
M|Step|tx|\| Later cohorts are larger but retain worse \| Growth is outpacing pd qual \| Slow growth; fix retention before scaling \|
M|Pira|Dave|
M|Acqu|**Qu|** How do us find you?
M|Acqu|tx|\| Metric \| Formula \| Good Benchmark \|
M|Acqu|tx|\|--------\|---------\|----------------\|
M|Acqu|tx|\| Visitor-to-signup rate \| Signups / Unique visitors \| 2-5% for B2C, 5-15% for B2B \|
M|Acqu|tx|\| Cost per acquisition (CPA) \| mk spend / New signups \| Varies by industry; must be below LTV \|
M|Acqu|tx|\| Channel mix \| % of signups by source \| No single channel > 50% (diversification) \|
M|Acti|**Qu|** Do us have a great first exp?
M|Acti|tx|\| Metric \| Formula \| Good Benchmark \|
M|Acti|tx|\|--------\|---------\|----------------\|
M|Acti|tx|\| Onboarding completion rate \| us completing setup / Signups \| 60-80% \|
M|Acti|tx|\| Time to first value \| Time from signup to core action \| Under 5 minutes for consumer; under 1 day for B2B \|
M|Acti|tx|\| Aha moment conversion \| us reaching key milestone / Signups \| 40-70% \|
M|Rete|**Qu|** Do us come back?
M|Rete|tx|\| Metric \| Formula \| Good Benchmark \|
M|Rete|tx|\|--------\|---------\|----------------\|
M|Rete|tx|\| Day 1 / Day 7 / Day 30 retention \| Active on Day N / Cohort size \| Varies by category (see below) \|
M|Rete|tx|\| Weekly active / Monthly active ratio \| WAU / MAU \| 25%+ is healthy \|
M|Rete|tx|\| Churn rate \| us lost / Total us per period \| Under 5% monthly for SaaS \|
M|Rete|**Re|**
M|Rete|tx|\| Category \| Day 1 \| Day 7 \| Day 30 \|
M|Rete|tx|\|----------\|-------\|-------\|--------\|
M|Rete|tx|\| sl/messaging \| 50-70% \| 30-50% \| 20-35% \|
M|Rete|tx|\| E-commerce \| 25-40% \| 10-20% \| 5-15% \|
M|Rete|tx|\| SaaS (B2B) \| 80-95% \| 70-85% \| 60-80% \|
M|Rete|tx|\| Mobile gaming \| 35-50% \| 15-25% \| 5-15% \|
M|Rete|tx|\| Productivity tools \| 40-60% \| 25-40% \| 15-30% \|
M|rv|**Qu|** How do you make money?
M|rv|tx|\| Metric \| Formula \| Good Benchmark \|
M|rv|tx|\|--------\|---------\|----------------\|
M|rv|tx|\| Average rv per us (ARPU) \| Total rv / Active us \| Depends on pricing md \|
M|rv|tx|\| Lifetime value (LTV) \| ARPU multiplied by average lifespan \| 3x+ CAC \|
M|rv|tx|\| Conversion to paid \| Paid us / Total active us \| 2-5% freemium; 15-30% free trial \|
M|rv|tx|\| Net rv retention \| (Starting MRR + expansion - contraction - churn) / Starting MRR \| 100%+ for B2B SaaS \|
M|Refe|**Qu|** Do us tell others?
M|Refe|tx|\| Metric \| Formula \| Good Benchmark \|
M|Refe|tx|\|--------\|---------\|----------------\|
M|Refe|tx|\| Viral coefficient (K) \| Invites per us multiplied by conversion rate of invites \| Above 0.5 is strong; above 1.0 is viral \|
M|Refe|tx|\| Net Promoter Score (NPS) \| % Promoters minus % Detractors \| 40+ is excellent \|
M|Refe|tx|\| Referral rate \| us who refer / Total active us \| 10%+ indicates strong word of mouth \|
M|Refe|tx|\| Organic traffic share \| Organic visits / Total visits \| 40%+ suggests br strength \|
M|Pre-|tx|Focus on engagement and retention. rv metrics are premature.
M|Pre-|**Pr|**
M|Pre-|it|Retention (Week 1, Week 4 by cohort)
M|Pre-|it|Core action completion rate
M|Pre-|- Qu|Sean Ellis tst ("How wld you feel if you cld no longer use this pd?")
M|Pre-|it|NPS from active us
M|Pre-|it|sn frequency
M|Pre-|**Do|** CAC, LTV, rv, viral coefficient. These are meaningless w/o pd-mk fit.
M|Post|tx|Focus on unit economics and channel efficiency.
M|Post|**Pr|**
M|Post|it|LTV and LTV/CAC ratio
M|Post|it|CAC by channel
M|Post|it|Monthly retention and churn by cohort
M|Post|it|rv per us tn
M|Post|it|Activation rate
M|Post|**Do|** br awareness, mk share, total rv. Scale metrics come after unit economics are healthy.
M|Grow|tx|Focus on efficiency at scale and sustainable growth.
M|Grow|**Pr|**
M|Grow|it|Net rv retention
M|Grow|it|Payback period (months to recover CAC)
M|Grow|it|Gross margin
M|Grow|it|Growth rate (month over month)
M|Grow|it|Channel saturation indicators
M|Prin|tx|Each dashboard shd answer one question. Do not combine acquisition, engagement, and rv on a single screen. cr separate views for separate questions.
M|Prin|tx|A single number is meaningless w/o context. Always show the metric over time (at least 8 weeks) and compare to the previous period.
M|Prin|tx|Default views shd show cohort data. Aggregate views shd require a deliberate click or toggle. This prevents the team from accidentally reading vanity numbers.
M|Prin|tx|Percentages w/o absolute numbers mislead. "50% conversion rate" sounds great until you learn the sample was 4 us. Always show both the percentage and the underlying count.
M|Prin|tx|Add annotations to the dashboard showing when experiments launched. This creates a visual connection btw actions and results.
M|Comm|tx|\| Mistake \| Why It Is Wrong \| Correction \|
M|Comm|tx|\|---------\|----------------\|------------\|
M|Comm|tx|\| Tracking 30+ metrics simultaneously \| Attention is diluted; team cannot focus \| Pick 3-5 primary metrics per stage \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Celebrating total us growth while retention declines \| Growth masks pd problems \| Always lead w/ cohort retention \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Measuring weekly w/o cohort segmentation \| Cannot distinguish pd improvement from mk spend \| Segment every metric by cohort \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Setting metric targets after seeing results \| Confirmation bias; any result looks like sc \| Set targets before running experiments \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Ignoring qualitative data bc "we have the numbers" \| Numbers tell you what; interviews tell you why \| Pair every quantitative metric w/ 5-10 cs conversations per month \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Optimizing a metric that does not connect to business outcomes \| Local op w/o global impact \| Map every metric to a business outcome (retention to LTV, activation to retention, etc.) \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Changing metric definitions mid-experiment \| Results become incomparable \| Lock definitions before experiments start; cr new metrics if needed \|
M|Comm|tx|Good metrics cr honest conversations. Bad metrics cr comfortable delusions. The discipline of innovation accounting is choosing honesty over comfort.